{
  "_documentation": "ATT&CK mapping policy (auditex 2026-05-09): every rule_id maps to at least one MITRE ATT&CK technique where the threat is real (collector.issue.* diagnostics are exempt \u2014 they're operational, not adversarial). Email-auth controls (SPF/DKIM/DMARC/BIMI) anchor to T1566 (Phishing) parent and T1566.002 (Spearphishing Link) sub-technique because spoofed-domain phishing campaigns most commonly use links \u2014 attachment-based delivery (T1566.001) does not lean on SPF/DMARC alignment as heavily. Application-credential rules (expired/expiring/long-validity/dormant) anchor to T1078.004 (Valid Accounts: Cloud Accounts) for the credential-abuse vector and T1098.001 (Account Manipulation: Additional Cloud Credentials) when the rule directly enables credential creation/persistence. Cross-tenant access rules anchor to T1199 (Trusted Relationship) for inbound and T1567 (Exfiltration Over Web Service) for outbound; rogue-consent surfaces anchor to T1528 (Steal Application Access Token). Mailbox forwarding anchors to T1114.003 (Email Collection: Email Forwarding Rule) plus T1098 (Account Manipulation) and T1567 for external recipients; hide-from-user rules anchor to T1564.008 (Hide Artifacts: Email Hiding Rules). SharePoint broad-link sharing anchors to T1530 (Data from Cloud Storage). When in doubt, prefer the parent technique over a too-specific sub-technique.",
